\[\frac{\mathbf{n} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -6 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}}{\left\| \mathbf{n} \right\| \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -6 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \right\|} = \frac{\mathbf{n} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -12 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}}{\left\| \mathbf{n} \right\| \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -12 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \right\|}.\]Since $\left\| \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -6 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} \right\| = \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -12 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \right\|,$ this simplifies to
\[\mathbf{n} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -6 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} = \mathbf{n} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -12 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}.\]Let $\mathbf{n} = \begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \\ c \end{pmatrix}.$  Then
\[3a - 6b + 2c = 4a - 12b + 3c.\]This simplifies to $a - 6b + c = 0.$  Since $\mathbf{n}$ is a linear combination of $\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -6 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -12 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix},$ it is also a linear combination of $\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -6 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -6 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$ (the latter being the difference of the two normal vectors).  Hence,
\[\mathbf{n} = s \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -6 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} + t \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -6 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 3s + t \\ -6s - 6t \\ 2s + t \end{pmatrix}\]for some scalars $s$ and $t.$  Then
\[(3s + t) - 6(-6s - 6t) + (2s + t) = 0.\]This simplifies to $41s + 39t = 0,$ so we can take $s = 39$ and $t = -41,$ which gives us
\[\mathbf{n} = \begin{pmatrix} 76 \\ -300 \\ 97 \end{pmatrix}.\]The equation of the plane is then
\[76x - 300y + 97z + D = 0.\]Since $(-5,-1,-5)$ lies on the plane,
\[76(-5) - 300(-1) + 97(-5) + D = 0,\]so $D = 115.$  Thus, the equation of the plane is $\boxed{76x - 300y + 97z + 115 = 0}.$

